      "body": "Three main tools:\n\n1. **Strength performance (progressive overload):** The single best indicator you're gaining muscle is gaining strength within the program's rep ranges (~8–15 reps), *not* 1RM strength. Lifting more weight or more reps at the same weight = likely adding muscle. Track weight and reps for as many exercises as possible to \"beat the logbook.\"\n2. **Progress photos:** The most direct measure since the goal is getting more jacked. Take roughly every 2–3 months (no more than once a week). Use the same camera, background, and lighting; take front, side, and rear shots.\n3. **Bodyweight:** Useful alongside the other two. Aim to gain ~**1–2% of bodyweight per month** to keep gains mostly muscle (e.g. a 170 lb / 77 kg lifter gains ~1.7–3.4 lb / 0.7–1.5 kg per month). Slower gain = leaner. For fat loss, lose no faster than **0.5–1% of bodyweight per week**. For recomp, roughly maintain weight and use photos + strength as the guide. Watch weekly trends/averages, not single weigh-ins. Calipers/DEXA/BIA are not recommended for tracking due to low accuracy [16].\n\n---"
